Super Eagles coach José Peseiro yesterday joined the team camp in the United States ahead of tomorrow’s friendly against Mexico at the AT&T Stadium, Arlington. The Portuguese also had a brief meeting with the coaching crew while the Eagles had their first training session under the new coach. Following the Super Eagles’ failed bid to qualify for the 2022 World Cup in Qatar, the Nigeria Football Federation (NFF) announced the 62-year-old as the new national team manager as a replacement for Augustine Eguavoen who served in an interim capacity after German Gernot Rohr was fired last December.   UCL final comes alive on GOTv      PARIS 2O22: Cubana hosts Liverpool, Real UCL showdown     ITTF Africa Cup: Aruna  leads others into knockouts   The former Venezuela national team coach is expected to lead Nigeria to the 2023 AFCON in Cote D’Ivoire but will first face a qualifying stage against Sierra Leone, Mauritius and Guinea Bissau. The Eagles camp officially opened yesterday as the delegation from Nigeria arrived in Dallas, Texas early yesterday with some players, coaches, and backroom staff based in Nigeria. Among the Europe-based players that joined the camp yesterday were William Troost-Ekong, Ola Aina, Alex Iwobi, Semi Ajayi, and Moses Simon and the team would have had its first training session at 6 pm Dallas, Texas time). Already, 13 players were on the ground for the tie against Mexico, and among them were Adewale Adeyinka (Akwa United), Ojo Olorunleke (Enyimba FC), Ibrahim Buhari (Plateau United), Chiamaka Madu (Rivers United), Is’haq Rafiu (Rivers United), Victor Mbaoma (Enyimba FC), Faisal Sanni (Katsina United), Babatunde Bello (Akwa United) while other invited players are expected in camp today. However, seventeen players are still expected to team up with the squad in the United States as Nigeria trade tackles with the World Cup-bound South American and North American teams.